{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15090"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15090"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.14,0.05,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67913"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7778"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15090"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"9877"},{"type":"tags","id":"9879"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18983"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67913"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPost-obstructive diuresis occurs following relief of urinary tract obstruction, often resulting in excessive urine output. During the period of obstruction, several compensatory changes occur in the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary pathophysiological change seen in post-obstructive diuresis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Downregulation of sodium transporters and aquaporin channels","Increased aldosterone secretion","Decreased atrial natriuretic peptide levels","Upregulation of aquaporin-2 expression","Increased antidiuretic hormone secretion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism in post-obstructive diuresis involves \u003Cstrong\u003Edownregulation of sodium transporters and aquaporin channels\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs during obstruction and persists after relief, leading to reduced sodium and water reabsorption in the tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased aldosterone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Aldosterone levels are typically decreased during the diuretic phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased atrial natriuretic peptide levels\u003C/strong\u003E - Atrial natriuretic peptide levels are actually elevated, promoting sodium and water excretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpregulation of aquaporin-2 expression\u003C/strong\u003E - Aquaporin channels are downregulated, not upregulated\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased antidiuretic hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Antidiuretic hormone levels are typically suppressed\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, the accumulation of urea and other osmotically active solutes during the period of obstruction contributes to the diuresis when the obstruction is relieved. These changes result in a marked increase in urine output as the kidney attempts to eliminate excess fluid and solutes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-obstructive diuresis involves downregulation of sodium transporters and aquaporin channels in the kidney tubules","Increased atrial natriuretic peptide and decreased antidiuretic hormone contribute to the diuresis","Accumulation of osmotically active solutes during obstruction promotes water excretion when relieved"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15090"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53378"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:40:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:42:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7778"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67913"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu